'''Tenno Shrine''' (天皇神社) is a {{ill|shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|12=draft}}{{ill|Otsu City|ja|大津市|12=draft}}.

== Geography ==
{{ill|JR West|ja|西日本旅客鉄道|lt=JR|lt_ja=JR|12=draft}}{{ill|Wani Station|ja|和邇駅|12=draft}} is located approximately 1.1 {{ill|kilometer|ja|キロメートル|12=draft}} to the southwest <ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/spot/detail/158|title=天皇神社{{!}}滋賀県観光情報|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=びわこビジターズビューロー|date=2015-06-23}}</ref>, and a 10‐minute walk away <ref name=":1">{{Cite web|和書|url=http://nishioumi.ct-net.com/00-05.shtml|title=歴史散歩・和邇天皇神社　和邇祭り|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=京都新聞西近江販売所連合|year=2000|month=05}}</ref>. It is situated along the roadside of Ryūka Crossing (present‐day {{ill|Shiga Prefecture Route 311, Tokochu Shiga Line|ja|滋賀県道311号途中志賀線|12=draft}}) {{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=20}}. It is about 5 minutes from {{ill|Kosai Road|ja|湖西道路|12=draft}} ({{ill|National Route 161|ja|国道161号|12=draft}}) {{ill|Wani IC|ja|和迩インターチェンジ|lt=Wani IC|lt_ja=和邇IC|12=draft}} <ref name=":2">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://otsu.or.jp/thingstodo/spot213|title=天皇神社|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=びわ湖大津観光協会}}</ref>.

== History ==
In 966 ({{ill|Kōhō|ja|康保|12=draft}} 3) the Gozu Tennō of {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社|12=draft}} was returned, and it is said that it began under the name "Wani Gozu Tennōsha" {{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=20}}. The enshrinement is said to have been established in the late {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|lt=Kamakura|lt_ja=鎌倉|12=draft}} <ref name=":0" />. In 1876 ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft}} 9) it acquired its current name {{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=20}}. At that time, it became a village shrine <ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=118|title=神社紹介　天皇神社（テンノウジンジャ）|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=滋賀県神社庁}}</ref>.

== Shrine Grounds ==
The main hall was constructed in {{ill|1324|ja|1324|12=draft}} (the first year of {{ill|Shōchū|ja|正中 (元号)|lt=Shōchū|lt_ja=正中|12=draft}}) and has been designated as an {{ill|Important Cultural Property|ja|重要文化財|12=draft}} {{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=20}}. This main hall is one of only three examples of {{ill|Gabled Roof Construction|ja|切妻造|12=draft}} in Shiga Prefecture (the others can be seen at {{ill|Ono Takamura Shrine|ja|小野篁神社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ono Dōfū Shrine|ja|小野道風神社|12=draft}}) <ref name=":0" />. The format of having three main halls with a rear worship space in a gabled structure is rare nationwide <ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www5.city.otsu.shiga.jp/kankyou/content.asp?key=0401000000&skey=207|title=大津のかんきょう宝箱　天皇神社（和邇中）|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=大津市環境部環境政策課}}</ref>. A characteristic feature from the time of its establishment is the remaining outline of a {{ill|Toad‐leg Motif|ja|蟇股|12=draft}} <ref name=":0" />. The roof is made of {{ill|Cypress Bark Roofing|ja|檜皮葺|12=draft}} <ref name=":2" />.

== Annual Festival ==
The annual festival of Tenno Shrine, known as "Wani Festival" and sometimes referred to as "Goka Festival" <ref name=":1" />, is held by shrine officials from the Wani‐naka area and the districts of {{ill|Minamihama|ja|南浜|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nakahama|ja|中浜|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kitahama|ja|北浜|12=draft}}, {{ill|Imaju|ja|今宿|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Takashiro|ja|高城|12=draft}} <ref name=":1" />. In the Minamihama district, on the early morning of the festival day, shrine officials depart from {{ill|Kimoto Shrine|ja|木元神社|12=draft}} to Tenno Shrine, and in the afternoon, portable shrines from other regions proceed to the lakeside resting area <ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.rekihaku.otsu.shiga.jp/db/jiten/data/245.html|title=和邇祭{{!}}歴史事典|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=大津市歴史博物館}}</ref>. Its origin is attributed to the incident during {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|12=draft}}'s assault on {{ill|Mount Hiei Arson (1571)|ja|比叡山焼き討ち (1571st year )|lt=Mount Hiei Arson|lt_ja=比叡山焼き討ち|12=draft}}, when the portable shrine of {{ill|Hiyoshi Taisha|ja|日吉大社|12=draft}} fled to Tenno Shrine, which subsequently led to conflicts over its return <ref name=":1" />. It was once held annually on May 8, but nowadays, due to holiday scheduling, it is observed on the second Sunday of May each year <ref name=":1" />.

