The main hall was constructed in [[:en:1324|1324]] (the first year of [[:en:Shōchū (era)|Shōchū]]) and has been designated as an [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] {{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=20}}. This main hall is one of only three examples of {{ill|Gabled Roof Construction|ja|切妻造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gabled Roof Construction|qq=|1=rake-overhanging gabled roof|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q13308575}} in Shiga Prefecture (the others can be seen at {{ill|Ono Takamura Shrine|ja|小野篁神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ono Takamura Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Ono Dōfū Shrine|ja|小野道風神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ono Dōfū Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}) <ref name=":0" />. The format of having three main halls with a rear worship space in a gabled structure is rare nationwide <ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www5.city.otsu.shiga.jp/kankyou/content.asp?key=0401000000&skey=207|title=大津のかんきょう宝箱　天皇神社（和邇中）|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=大津市環境部環境政策課}}</ref>. A characteristic feature from the time of its establishment is the remaining outline of a {{ill|Toad‐leg Motif|ja|蟇股|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toad‐leg Motif|qq=|1=kaerumata|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q123117911}} <ref name=":0" />. The roof is made of {{ill|Cypress Bark Roofing|ja|檜皮葺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cypress Bark Roofing|qq=|1=cypress bark roof|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q90373477}} <ref name=":2" />.

== Annual Festival ==
The annual festival of Tenno Shrine, known as "Wani Festival" and sometimes referred to as "Goka Festival" <ref name=":1" />, is held by shrine officials from the Wani‐naka area and the districts of {{ill|Minamihama|ja|南浜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamihama|qq=|1=Minamihama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11408105}}, {{ill|Nakahama|ja|中浜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakahama|qq=|1=Nakahama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q16283273}}, {{ill|Kitahama|ja|北浜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitahama|qq=|1=Kitahama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11402355}}, {{ill|Imaju|ja|今宿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imaju|qq=|1=Imaju|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11376872}}, and {{ill|Takashiro|ja|高城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takashiro|qq=|1=Takashiro|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11669044}} <ref name=":1" />. In the Minamihama district, on the early morning of the festival day, shrine officials depart from {{ill|Kimoto Shrine|ja|木元神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kimoto Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} to Tenno Shrine, and in the afternoon, portable shrines from other regions proceed to the lakeside resting area <ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.rekihaku.otsu.shiga.jp/db/jiten/data/245.html|title=和邇祭{{!}}歴史事典|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=大津市歴史博物館}}</ref>. Its origin is attributed to the incident during [[:en:Oda Nobunaga|Oda Nobunaga]]'s assault on {{ill|Mount Hiei Arson (1571)|ja|比叡山焼き討ち (1571st year )|lt=Mount Hiei Arson|lt_ja=比叡山焼き討ち|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Hiei Arson (1571)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, when the portable shrine of [[:en:Hiyoshi Taisha|Hiyoshi Taisha]] fled to Tenno Shrine, which subsequently led to conflicts over its return <ref name=":1" />. It was once held annually on May 8, but nowadays, due to holiday scheduling, it is observed on the second Sunday of May each year <ref name=":1" />.

